title: Inmoov updated RotPotentioV2 for New Square potentiometers

description.text:
The new Hitec servos for Inmoov now have square potentiometers and the original files do not work. I tried several other designs on this site and most do not work as the hole is not centered and this will put undo stress on the potentiometers.

The original rounds could easily be spun in the hole to fine tune the zero position. This design puts the square pot into a round holder which then can be spun.

Please verify that the pots have not changed again, check to make sure the pot fits into the slot with no stress. Place a small screw next to the center spinner or in the gap to hold things still

title: Dark souls Estus Flask with screw on top.

description.text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G-wkbElmebk&feature=youtu.be

The Estus flask from the Dark souls series, there are two versions, a smooth one and a textured one that try's to emulate the games design. The models have been leak tested for over a week. The container holds about 6 oz(half a soda can). You can resize up as much as you want, resizing down however might cause leaks as the walls will become thinner. The threads are very tight to help make a good seal, if that doesn't matter to you, you can resize the top to about 2-5 percent smaller than the bottom. One of the tops have supports in the model itself to help save on plastic and to make sure the threads turn out right.

comments.text: I'll get a picture up when I have a moment, but just for anyone wondering, if you want this to be "shot sized", scale it down to 63-65% the normal size. That will reduce the total volume to roughly a quarter the size, which since this can hold 6 oz at 100% size, 1/4 the volume would be 1.5 oz. I've had this sitting on my desk at work filled with water for about three or so hours and I'm not seeing any water seeping through, so I'd say its good in the short term. I'll try testing it for longer periods when I have the time to do so.

description.text:
I bought two IKEA Trogsta lamps a couple of years ago. They hold sentimental value, so when both of them broke at the base, we patched them with electrical tape, rubberbands, and whatever it took to have the tripod-like design work.

This part hopefully fixes a fragile part by design, making the lamp strong, and useful again.

The part was designed with Autodesk Fusion 360 in just a couple of hours, with no real experience using the software before that. I really recommend it to quickly iterate.

Measure metal leg

I started tracing one of the three metal legs on paper, and then taking general measures.
The end of the leg has a specific geometry, which you don't really need to replicate to make a good fit in the base.

Model the base

The base is mostly an extruded circumference, and modified rectangular container in a circular array.

I didn't include the cable holder, as it actually makes the lamp prone to falling down.
This is a fidget spinner with 3 bearing holes, each is for a 22mm Diameter bearing.

title: Tiny mATX case
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I needed a small-as-possible case for an mATX motherboard that can accomodate a full-height graphic card. This is as small as it can get, with the width and depth of the case just enough for the board, and the height just enough for the graphics card.

NOTE that this is for a smaller-than-standard mATX board, at 235mm x 185mm (as opposed to a full-size mATX board at 243mm x 243mm). But boards like this are fairly common, plus the design should be fairly straightforward to adjust to different board sizes.

It should also be easy enough to modify this into a closed case. There is still room for an extra SSD and a full 3.5in HDD (if we ditch the side fan and ensure to only use low-power CPUs like the Intel T series); or to put a liquid cooler there if we want to use a higher powered CPU.

EDIT: uploaded an old version of the dxf file. New one should be up now

Everything was done from scratch, but I referred to the mATX specification v1.2 as well as the PCI specification for the exact dimensions. The biggest space savers are putting the SFX PSU atop a low-profile/liquid CPU cooler and ditching all the bays.

I used QCAD for the design, which is free and opensource. It doesn't have 3D rendering, but for something as simple as this it's sufficient. Plus it uses .dxf file format.

This was cut on a cheap ($340) Chinese 40W CO2 laser, using Baltic Birch 1/8in plywood. 16mm/s on 12mA (~80% power) cuts through this plywood like butter. Just need to pay attention to the dimensions of the pieces.

The small bars are only mainly for cable management, not structural. They can be removed as desired.

In areas with high humidity, acrylic would be a better material than plywood as they don't warp.

I began this drawing as a simple introduction to modeling in Fusion 360 and a bit of a "Hello World" assignment for Thingiverse. This 17mm wrench was developed specifically for adjusting the Z-Axis sensor on the Printrbot Simple Metal. This wrench has been designed with a web that adds strength to the jaws of the tool – preventing the plastic jaws of the wrench from deforming under stress. This is a whirligig centrifuge. I saw this video https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qf-D1Upn-KU about a team at Stanford that came up with using a simple little toy as a centrifuge to use in 3rd world countries for disease diagnosis. Hats off to them! I thought I'd give it a "whirl," so I designed this that can be 3D printed, laser cut or cut out of cardboard. It uses zip ties to hold the tubes on (string could maybe work) and some string tied and taped to some pencils.This is designed to work with 1.5 mL centrifuge tubes that you can get from amazon or other online suppliers. It can go over 5000 rpm (I have no way to really test it).

It can be used to extract DNA from test samples and for other cool science demonstrations like taking the powder out of hot chocolate.

It can be a little difficult to get to start. The trick is to get a lot of revolutions on it and then pull slowly.

There's a .stl and a .STEP if you want to 3D print it or laser cut it. I also made a simple template that can be glued onto some cardboard to cut it out and to add strength. It would probably work best with cardstock paper.

description.text:
This is a study of ball socket joints printed in situ. There are several BSJ models around but all print components separately. So i wanted to see if it can be printed in assembly, and i got it to work! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mfWnMXuzFdk

These joints have about 180 of freedom around one axis plus 360 rotation.

Yes

0.1

100

Notes:

The outer shape needs support when printing (bed support only!), the joint also needed support but since I don't know how to set specific supports in Cura, there is one support column in the model itself.

This is printed at 100% infill for strength, if you scale the thing up, you can probably go with whichever settings you are comfortable with, like 1 mm shell and 15% infill.

This is not symmetrical, if you print the model upside down it will most probably not work

First clear external support structures, then snap the joints, it is easy and doesn't need any tools. Just move them along the direction of intended movement, there will be a little resistance at first, then the support structure breaks and the joint starts moving freely.

I started printing http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1116392 and got tired of getting balls and sockets to match. But this is 3D printing, why not print the assemblies in one go? First i tried printing a BSJ vertically, it almost worked but the neck of the ball would snap easily, no matter how hot i would print it. Printing at higher temperatures creates better bonds between the layers. Then i figured out that with little support this can be printed horizontally.

I have thick fingers, so switching filament quickly can be difficult with the standard idler arm and latch.

I also found that the idler arm wore a lot at the point where the filament first came through, so I made it into a funnel shape to improve the life of the idler arm. I also made the point where the filament went through a funnel shape to reduce wear on the idler arm. The funnel in the arm also helps change filament, guiding stiff 2.85 filament into the hot end.
I also put a tab on the side to quickly open and close the idler arm.

You can now open and close the head quickly with one hand, which is great for when you want to quickly change filament colors.

When combined these two are an improvement on the factory printed idler arms and latches.

description.text:
A tube-shaped alarm-clock based on an earlier design made from a plumbing tube. The Tube integrates a speaker meant to fit in halogen light fixture holes with a diameter of about 80mm. The clock has one big snooze button as well as 3 smaller buttons used to set the alarm functions.

The front 7 Segment display is a .56" 7-segment I2C display module. The alarm is generated by a I2S class-d audio amp module. Everything is driven by an esp8266 module and a 5v mains voltage psu module is integrated into the case separated by an insert from the low voltage electronics. I have used a non-3d printed "figure-8" power connector for my design but it should be easy to make a plate to connect a fixed Power cable if you cannot get the right type.

I have included the .scad files so you can easily modify the parts for your own stuff should you need to. I recommend putting 1mm self-adhesive rubber sheeting into the indentations in the base - thats what they are meant for after all but as always with my builds this is not a requirement and optional.

Tinkercad

Project

I haven't yet in my hands the 'gimmick', so, knowing it's exact dimensions, I began to draw in Tinkercad a support that fits my (future) D-bot e3D-V6 extruder.
The support utilizes the 2 lower fan screws of e3D-V6 and the enclosure can slide up and down for little adjustments where necessary (about 5mm total).
The sensor sensitivity is 5mm and shoul work well with 3mm borosilicate glass.
If an underneath aluminium heater interferes, may be necessary paint it in black.

BOM and instructions

You need only:

  • n. 2 M3x10mm or more depending of where you fix the support
  • n. 1 M3x5mm screw
  • n. 3 M5 washer
  • n. 1 M3 nut
  • n. 1 flat 4 pin connector
  • n. 3 cables

I marked the enclosure with pin connections ( Ground - Signal - n.c. - +5-24Vdc).

Fix the nut into the hexagonal hole; with some pressure it stays firm in place.

Once fixed to extruder, adjust the enclosure to the right height from bed and tight the screw.

Connect the 3 pins to the board Z endstop socket, paying great attention to not invert polarity when connecting to your board, you could fry it!

The autoleveling procedure is not covered here.

Caveat

This is only a theoretic project.
If someone already own a e3d-V6, please inform me about discrepancies...

This gyroid cup is intended to check math fact that gyroid is a 3D surface that splits space into two isolated subspaces. So you can check that you can fill this cup with two liquids that don't mix to each other.
Fill one part of the cup with some liquid. Make sure the other part of the cup is still dry and fill the remaining part with some other liquid.

Notes:

Support is required for cup handle print. Don't use support everywhere with gyroid. :)

Gyroid generation

First of all I created gyroid using OpenSCAD.
Gyroid is described/approximated by equation sin(x)cos(y)+sin(y)cos(z)+sin(z)cos(x)=0;
so I included points that match criteria abs(sin(x)cos(y)+sin(y)cos(z)+sin(z)cos(x)) < 0.2;
for each such point of grid I created a cube with size of grid cell plus epsilon (required to properly produce union in OpenSCAD). Then I used OpenSCAD and PC with 16Gb RAM to generate gyroid cell using this simple program.
After that I loaded gyroid element and imported it into Blender. I united 8 such elements into cube of double size. Then imported the cup model, I created for this thing using OpenSCAD, and united it with gyroid.
Unfortunately OpenSCAD is very slow and memory consuming for union operations with heavy objects, so Blender was just the only way to produce final result.

VITAMINS:
1 36" 8mm polished rod (McMaster 88625K67) - buy extras for other projects ;) TOOLS

• Working CALIBRATED printer
  • 6.5mm drill
  • Allen wrench for 3mm socket
  • Hacksaw or 3.5" die-grinder with cutting wheel
  • Heat gun or hair dryer
    • INSTRUCTIONS

NOTE - all prints were done by author using KISSlicer.

  • Print the part

  • Clean part by trimming any overhangs on the the nut end and by using the 6.5mm drill down the clearance hole in the center

  • Cut two 14" pieces from the rod. I used a 3.5" die grinder with a cutting wheel, hack saw should work. After cutting sand the ends to remove any burrs. The 14" length results in about 3" of excess rod above the bearings (and 1" above the top of the y carriage).

  • with the printer near home replace the existing rods with the new longer rods. In the dry winter air I was able to twist each one out and replace one at a time so that I did not have to lift the carriage off the top.

  • Run the printer to close to the top of the Z-axis.

  • While supporting the carriage remove the two screws holding in the acme nut

  • push the carriage down so the acme nut pops up. Unscrew the nut.

  • lift the carriage and set it on the end of the acme rod or prop up using one of the old rods

  • fit acme nut into part. Use heat gun/hair dryer to slightly warm part if it doesn't fit.

  • While watching wiring, life carriage high enough that slide in the part at an angle to the motor from the bottom with notch facing motor. I found that if I screwed the part on the acme screw first it doesn't fit.

  • turn rod to thread into nut. MANUALLY turn rod to drop to home position while checking that wires are not catching If the nut hits your motor-to-rod vinyl tub before reaching home you can lossen the screws at the top of the part to allow it to "sit above" the plywood.

  • In Repetitier edit printer settings -> printer shape and change Print Area Height to 160

  • In KissSlicer edit printer -> hardware and set bed size Z to 160

title: Zortrax M200 dual airflow radial fan duct
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Description (dual_flow_extr_shroud_V7B.stl)

This is an alternative way to having a double cooling flow on the area of extrusion.
The most popular way is to use a second axial fan installed on one of the many special bracket that can be found here on Thingiverse. I myself have published one here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1901911
Later I saw an anular shroud for Wanhao D6 by ZincBoy and I really liked the idea ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1666096 ).
The use of a radial fan is almost mandatory for this application, either for lack of space, both because the axial fans are characterized by a too low working pressure. The problem with the radial fan that I have chosen and which is the same used by ZincBoy is that it does not survive to the 24V PWM with which is powered.
Another problem is that if powered at 12V is so effective that the printing aborts due excessive extruder cooling.
So a small divider/filter circuit is necessary. The divider that I use allows you to print without problems up to 60% fan speed. If you want to print at a higher air flow you must isolate the hotend, for example with cotton coats that can be found on the market or you can use smaller heating block.
The circuit can be easily accommodated in the tray below the fan.
You can find the radial fan here: http://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/delta-electronics/BFB0412HHA-A117/603-1840-ND/5022816

The design is meant to be printed without supports. Because of supportless design it might seem that the air flow is directed towards the hotend. Instead, the output ducts are designed to direct the air flow with a good downward angle.

You need a heat-resistant filament and that does not collapse with long bridges. The best results can be obtained with PBT filament and annealing in the oven, one hour at 60° C, one hour at 95° C, one hour at 60° C and then left to cool in the oven.
Also, three M3x25mm screws are necessary to secure the fan duct to the cooling block.

[EDIT 11/22/2017]
Well, you can now completely avoid electronics.
The radial fans shown at the link below tolerate the 24V PWM signal of the Zortrax M200, turn slower, are very silent and with the correct air volume.
https://it.aliexpress.com/item/2PCS-Gdstime-3D-Printer-Fan-40mm-12V-4010-Turbo-Blower-Cooling-Fans-with-120cm-Cable/32811510363.html?spm=a2g0y.10010108.1000023.9.19306e00p907zT

[EDIT 12/06/2017]
Z-VENT_SLP_V4b.stl added.
If you use the radial fan of aliexpress and do not need any adaptation electronics, this is a lightened variant and optimized in various aspects:

> the main air duct has fewer obstacles, in particular the air intake window

> an area that created strong turbulence was eliminated

> to free the entry obstruction, I removed the third fixing front screw

> to improve the solidity of the assembly I have expanded the support base of the two rear supports

> added a curved fin at the entrance that supports the long bridge

> added two cable supports

The downside is the fact that this time it is necessary to put some supports. This is not possible with Zsuite V1, because the supports would also be generated inside the air duct. It should be possible to slice with Zsuite beta2.2 which has a more advanced support management, but I got the best results with Simplify3D, translating the gcode into zcode using ZTool.
For those interested in using third-party slicers with the Zortrax M200 this page may interest you: https://www.stampa3d-forum.it/forum/topic/4107-zdump-is-dead-long-live-ztool /

[EDIT 02/03/2018]
Z-VENT_SLP_V4b.stl has been replaced with Z-VENT_V9.stl.
The main improvement concerns the distance from bed of the rear area, to avoid collision with the perforated bed connector. Minimum adjustments to the inclinations of unsupported areas.

title: Anet A8 Steel Frame (CHAVO A8)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
There is no need to print new parts and change current settings; this frame was designed for a straight swap of all parts from the acrylic to an all steel chassis. This will give the Anet a top class rigid frame. To save materials, screws, and nuts, this new design allows the use of most of the M3 screws and new 3/16" screws. The CHAVO A8 is the ultimate Anet A8 steel frame upgrade. This frame design not only looks amazing but greatly improves the quality of your prints. This is a DXF file with the design of the CHAVO A8; the file is set up and ready to be taken to a waterjet cutting facility, a laser cutting facility, or a plasma cutting facility. This design was cut with a waterjet cutter and tested for 3 months. The rigid frame is designed to use 3/16 inch plate steel or 3/16 inch aluminum. Imperial units were used to design the frame due to the availability and cost of metal in the USA. This frame is compatible as a straight swap of all components from the acrylic Anet A8 3D printer to this new steel or aluminum design.

Please go to the following site for more information and to purchase the frame design.

https://chavostyle.com/

View pictures and browse through upcoming content. A build log containing links to upgrades, galleries, parts, and slicer profiles coming soon.

description.text:
Now updated with MK3.1 - Which allows you to generate power!

A vertical turbine design which will turn freely in the wind, or when printing Base_Motor, you can use it in conjunction with a motor to generate power.

The motor used in my design is a 28mm diameter printer motor. If you decide to use a smaller motor, you could possibly print a spacer of some sort. You will also need to print the Arms_Gear and Motor Gear files, or if you wish to run a pulley system instead, then print the Arms_Pulley and Motor_Pulley files and find yourself an elastic band!

The Arms_Gear / Arms_Pulley files can be attached to the arms with 2 - 4x 25mm or longer M4 bolts

The turbine can be built in layers - I built a two layer version, as per the image.

The arms are printed in sets (Arms_Top & Arms_Bottom combine to make one set)
For a single tier turbine you need 2 sets, for a double tier turbine you need 3 sets, etc.

The design uses standard skateboard bearings and a length of 8mm threaded rod - I would recommend a minimum length of around 200mm for a single tier.

The Blades are held on the arms with M4 machines screws/bolts and secured with a nut on the other side - I would recommend at least 20mm length screws for a single blade, or 25-30mm for doubled up blades (Where the arm holds a blade on the top and bottom)

For Blog updates, please follow the link to my website - http://www.samrobmoe-design.co.uk/topics/3d-printing/vert-turbine

PLEASE NOTE:
The wind turbine must be firmly and securely mounted at your own risk. I am not responsible for any damages to property or people resulting from the turbine coming loose and/or breaking during use.

Notes:

For the Blades and possibly the bottom mount, print with supports on!

Attach a nylock nut to the end of the threaded rod, then slide it through the bottom of the mount. Attach another nut on the other side of the mount to ensure the rod is held solidly in the mount.

The bearings fit in holes on the part named 'Top' and the bearings should be facing downwards towards the mount.

The blades are held to the arms on the 'top' part with M4 machine screws/bolts.

The holes cut through the side of the bottom mount are intended to allow you to cable tie the turbine down. I had the turbine attached to a balcony railing.

Looking at a few different designs, I have tried to explore the shapes that seem to arise in most designs.

This is the MK2 version of the turbine, MK1 had several iterations, mainly looking at blade design.

This is a Battery Breakout Adaptor for the Range of Ozito (Bunnings) 18v power tools .
It connects directly to the power tools , as the normal battery would. It has a built in Spring latch to lock it in place . It can then be adapted to a range of batteries from other brands of power tools .It has been specifically designed to screw directly on to the really neat "Makita Battery Mount" designed & posted by Gary Platek , which can be found at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:352094
This allows it to connect directly to the Range of Makita 18V Lithium-Ion battery packs .

Small "L" shaped electrical terminals need to be cut from thin guage sheet metal .They fit neatly through the printed slots in the main body ,& can be securly screwed into place in the printed mounting holes , with self tapping screws .Bend them as shown it the photo, to give them a spring action to the electrical contact . Terminal lugs are used for power connection .
If you are connecting to the "Makita Battery Mount" use our " Makita 18V battery Terminal" http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2156290 & the connections will line up so that compression springs can be used make the electrical connection with no need for wiring

description.text: So here is my first try and designing something hope it is useful to someone. This dock is designed for a Samsung S6 Edge with a jell case on it but would fit a lot of phones with just some adjustment to the port location. I was having trouble with it warping when I printed it so added the ears to hold down the corners after the first several layers I paused the print and used capton tape to tape the ears down. I used 2 part epoxy to glue the charger into the port after trimming, I missed the location by about 0.4mm I tried to adjust for this file but make sure to test fit before gluing anything.
